  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is melatonin safe to take every night long-term?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Melatonin is considered safe for short-term nightly use (up to 3 months) in healthy adults. Long-term safety data beyond 2 years is limited. The American Academy of Sleep Medicine recommends periodic breaks, such as 3 weeks on and 1 week off, to prevent psychological reliance. Consult your healthcare provider before using melatonin nightly for more than 3 months, especially if you take blood thinners, immunosuppressants, or diabetes medications.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can you take too much melatonin?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. While melatonin is not toxic in the traditional sense, doses above 5mg can cause next-day grogginess, headaches, nausea, dizziness, and vivid nightmares. Research from MIT found that 0.3mg was sufficient to raise blood melatonin to normal nighttime levels. Doses of 10mg or higher are considered supraphysiological and may actually disrupt sleep architecture rather than improve it. More is not better with melatonin — start with the lowest dose available.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Does melatonin cause dependency?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Melatonin does not cause physical dependency or chemical addiction. Unlike prescription sleep aids such as benzodiazepines or Z-drugs, your body does not develop pharmacological tolerance to melatonin. However, some people develop a psychological reliance — they feel unable to fall asleep without it, even though their body still produces melatonin naturally. Cycling usage (3 weeks on, 1 week off) and maintaining strong sleep hygiene habits help prevent this pattern.' },
    },
