      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I take melatonin gummies before bed?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Take melatonin gummies 30 to 60 minutes before your intended bedtime. This timing allows blood melatonin levels to peak as you want to fall asleep. Taking melatonin too early (2+ hours before bed) means levels may decline before you need them. Taking it right at bedtime means peak levels arrive after you are already trying to sleep. Consistency matters — take melatonin at the same time each night for the best results.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are melatonin gummies safe for kids?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Some melatonin gummies are formulated for children ages 4 and older, but pediatric use should always be supervised by a pediatrician. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends addressing behavioral sleep factors first — consistent bedtime routines, limited screen time, cool dark rooms — before considering supplementation. If approved by a doctor, children should use the lowest available dose (0.5-1mg) and only as needed, not every night.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can pregnant or breastfeeding women take melatonin gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Pregnant and breastfeeding women should not take melatonin supplements without explicit approval from their OB-GYN or midwife. Melatonin is a hormone that crosses the placenta and passes into breast milk. While some research suggests it may be safe at low doses, the safety data during pregnancy and lactation is insufficient to make a blanket recommendation. Non-hormonal sleep strategies such as magnesium, chamomile tea, and sleep hygiene adjustments are generally preferred during pregnancy.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between natural and synthetic melatonin?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most melatonin supplements use synthetic melatonin, which is chemically identical to the hormone your body produces and is manufactured in a laboratory under controlled conditions. Natural melatonin is derived from animal pineal glands and carries a theoretical risk of contamination. A small number of brands use plant-derived melatonin from sources like tart cherry or rice, which is structurally identical to synthetic melatonin but appeals to consumers seeking a plant-based source. Functionally, all three forms are equivalent once absorbed.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do melatonin gummies work better than melatonin pills or capsules?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The active ingredient works the same regardless of delivery format. Gummies may absorb marginally faster because they begin dissolving in the mouth via sublingual absorption, but the difference is typically 5-10 minutes at most. The primary advantage of gummies is compliance — people are more likely to take their supplement consistently when it tastes good, and consistency is the single largest factor in whether melatonin works for you.' },
    },
  ],
};
