      <h2>Why Melatonin Gummies Have Become America's Top Sleep Supplement</h2>

      <p>The melatonin supplement market in the United States surpassed <strong>$1.5 billion in 2026</strong>, making it the single largest category in the sleep supplement industry. That figure has nearly tripled since 2019, driven by a convergence of factors: widespread sleep deprivation (the CDC reports one in three American adults regularly sleeps fewer than seven hours), growing distrust of prescription sleep medications, and increasing consumer preference for over-the-counter solutions that feel approachable rather than clinical. Melatonin gummies sit at the center of this market — they now outsell melatonin tablets, capsules, and liquid drops combined.</p>

      <p>The dominance of the gummy format is not accidental. Supplement compliance — whether people actually take what they buy — is the single largest factor determining whether any supplement works. Research published in the Journal of the American Pharmacists Association found that <strong>gummy supplements achieve 30-40% higher adherence rates than pills or capsules</strong>, primarily because people enjoy taking them. A supplement that sits unopened in a medicine cabinet provides zero benefit. A gummy that someone looks forward to taking every night at 9:30 PM provides consistent, cumulative benefit. This compliance advantage is why gummies have captured the majority of the melatonin market despite being slightly more expensive per serving than tablets.</p>

      <p>Choosing the right melatonin gummy, however, requires more than picking the best-selling option on Amazon. Melatonin dosages in commercial products range from 0.5mg to 10mg per serving — a twenty-fold difference — and the research on optimal dosing challenges the "more is better" assumption that many consumers bring to supplementation. Third-party testing certifications vary dramatically, with some brands earning rigorous USP or NSF verification while others make vague "tested" claims with no verifiable evidence. And the supporting ingredients alongside melatonin — L-Theanine, chamomile, valerian, magnesium, 5-HTP — create meaningfully different sleep experiences depending on why you struggle to sleep. This guide exists to cut through that complexity with data, testing, and clinical analysis.</p>
