    <section>
      <h2>Melatonin Dosing Science: What the Research Actually Says</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>The MIT Melatonin Study That Changed Everything</h3>
        <p>The most cited research on melatonin dosing comes from Dr. Richard Wurtman at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology — the scientist who first characterized melatonin's role in sleep regulation. His research demonstrated that <strong>a dose of just 0.3mg was sufficient to raise blood melatonin levels to their normal nocturnal range</strong> and effectively promote sleep onset in healthy adults. Critically, the study found that doses above 1mg raised melatonin to supraphysiological levels — far above what the body naturally produces — without improving sleep onset further.</p>

        <p>This finding has significant implications for consumers navigating the melatonin gummy market. The overwhelming majority of commercial products contain 3mg to 10mg per serving — three to thirty times the dose that MIT research identified as physiologically effective. Higher doses are not inherently dangerous for most adults, but they are associated with increased incidence of side effects including vivid dreams, next-morning grogginess, headaches, and paradoxically, disrupted sleep architecture. The "more is better" assumption that governs most supplement purchasing decisions does not apply to melatonin.</p>

        <h3>Melatonin Dose Tiers: Finding Your Optimal Range</h3>

        <table class="dose-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dose Range</th><th>Classification</th><th>Best For</th><th>Side Effect Risk</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>0.5 - 1mg</td><td>Low / Physiological</td><td>Mild sleep onset issues, first-time users, maintaining natural rhythm</td><td>Minimal — rarely causes side effects</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1 - 3mg</td><td>Standard</td><td>General sleep support, occasional insomnia, most adults</td><td>Low — occasional vivid dreams</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3 - 5mg</td><td>High</td><td>Jet lag recovery, shift work, moderate circadian disruption</td><td>Moderate — next-day grogginess possible</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5 - 10mg</td><td>Very High</td><td>Only under medical supervision or specific clinical need</td><td>Higher — headaches, nausea, disrupted sleep patterns</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Low Dose (0.5-1mg): The Research-Aligned Approach</h3>
        <p>Low-dose melatonin raises your blood levels to what they would be during a healthy, unassisted night. Products like <strong>Nordic Naturals (1.5mg)</strong> and <strong>ZzzQuil Pure Zzzs (1-2mg)</strong> operate in or near this range. Low doses are ideal for people who fall asleep 15-30 minutes later than they would like and want a gentle nudge toward drowsiness without next-day effects. This range is also the best starting point for anyone new to melatonin supplementation.</p>

        <h3>Standard Dose (3mg): The Most Common Commercial Dose</h3>
        <p>The 3mg dose is where most melatonin gummies land, including our top pick <strong>Olly Sleep</strong>. This dose exceeds what the MIT study identified as physiological but remains well-tolerated by the vast majority of healthy adults. It provides a more pronounced sleep onset signal than sub-milligram doses and is the most extensively studied dose in commercial supplement research. If you have used melatonin before and 1mg was not enough, 3mg is the logical next step.</p>

        <h3>High Dose (5-10mg): Proceed With Caution</h3>
        <p>Products like <strong>Natrol (5mg)</strong> and <strong>Vitafusion Max Strength (10mg)</strong> deliver doses that raise blood melatonin to 5-20 times natural levels. These doses have specific, narrow use cases: severe jet lag (especially eastward travel across 6+ time zones), rotating shift work, or physician-directed protocols for certain sleep disorders. They should not be the default choice for general sleep support, and anyone starting melatonin for the first time should begin at 1-3mg before considering these concentrations.</p>

        <h3>Natural Melatonin Sources vs. Synthetic Melatonin</h3>
        <p>Most melatonin supplements use synthetic melatonin — a laboratory-produced molecule that is chemically identical to the hormone your pineal gland secretes in response to darkness. A small number of products, including <strong>Garden of Life mykind Organics</strong>, source their melatonin from plant-based materials. Tart cherries are among the richest food sources of natural melatonin, which is why <strong>Nordic Naturals</strong> includes tart cherry extract alongside supplemental melatonin.</p>

        <p>Functionally, synthetic and natural melatonin are biochemically identical once absorbed. The choice between them is primarily philosophical rather than pharmacological. Consumers who prefer plant-derived supplements for ethical or environmental reasons will gravitate toward Garden of Life or Nordic Naturals. Those who prioritize cost and dose precision may prefer the more standardized delivery of synthetic melatonin products.</p>

        <h3>Melatonin Timing: When to Take Your Gummy</h3>
        <p>Take melatonin gummies <strong>30 to 60 minutes before your intended bedtime</strong>. This timing aligns with melatonin's pharmacokinetic profile — oral melatonin typically reaches peak blood concentration within 30-90 minutes of ingestion. Taking melatonin too early (2+ hours before bed) means levels may begin to decline before you need them. Taking it right at bedtime means peak levels arrive after you are already lying in bed waiting. Consistency matters as much as timing — taking melatonin at the same time each night trains your circadian system to anticipate the signal. For the complete pharmacokinetic breakdown, read our guide on <a href="/blog/how-long-does-melatonin-take-to-work/">how long does melatonin take to work</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

