    <section>
      <h2>How We Tested These Melatonin Gummies</h2>

      <div class="tested-box">
        <h3>Our Testing Methodology</h3>
        <p>Our evaluation was designed to provide actionable, evidence-based guidance that goes beyond marketing claims and Amazon star ratings. Here is exactly how we arrived at our rankings:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Independent Procurement:</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price from Amazon, Target, Walmart, or the brand's direct website. We accepted no free samples, sponsorships, affiliate-driven product placements, or early-access units. Our editorial independence is non-negotiable.</li>
          <li><strong>Ingredient Verification:</strong> Each formula was compared against published clinical research indexed on PubMed and the NIH Office of Dietary Supplements database. We evaluated whether melatonin dosages matched those used in peer-reviewed studies, whether supporting ingredients were present at clinically relevant concentrations, and whether the ingredient forms used were bioavailable.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-Party Testing Audit:</strong> We verified all third-party testing claims by checking certification databases directly — USP Verified Mark database, NSF International certified product listings, and Informed Sport's public registry. Products claiming "third-party tested" without verifiable certifications in any public database were flagged and noted in our reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>4-Week Testing Panel:</strong> A panel of 14 adults (ages 24-68, 8 women and 6 men) tested each melatonin gummy for four consecutive weeks. Participants reported sleep onset latency, subjective sleep quality, next-morning alertness, vivid dream frequency, and any side effects using the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) and custom daily logs.</li>
          <li><strong>Taste and Compliance Testing:</strong> Because compliance determines whether a supplement delivers any benefit at all, we scored every product on flavor, texture, aftertaste, sweetness balance, and overall enjoyment on a 1-10 scale. Products were also evaluated on packaging, ease of opening, and travel-friendliness.</li>
          <li><strong>Value Analysis:</strong> Total cost was divided by servings per container, then weighted against ingredient quality, dose accuracy, and third-party testing status to produce a composite value score. A cheap product with no testing certification is not "good value" — it is a gamble.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Final rankings were determined by a weighted scoring model: Ingredient Quality and Dosing (30%), Third-Party Testing (20%), Real-World Effectiveness from panel testing (25%), Taste and Compliance (10%), and Value (15%). The rankings on this page reflect those composite scores.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Who Should NOT Take Melatonin -->
    <section>
      <h2>Who Should Not Take Melatonin Gummies</h2>

      <p>While melatonin is considered safe for most healthy adults, certain populations should avoid supplementation without explicit medical approval:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Children under age 3:</strong> Melatonin supplementation in very young children has not been adequately studied. The developing endocrine system may be more sensitive to exogenous hormones.</li>
        <li><strong>Pregnant and breastfeeding women:</strong> Melatonin crosses the placenta and passes into breast milk. Safety data during pregnancy and lactation is insufficient for a blanket recommendation.</li>
        <li><strong>People with autoimmune conditions:</strong> Melatonin has immunomodulatory effects that may exacerbate autoimmune diseases including rheumatoid arthritis, lupus, and multiple sclerosis. Consult your rheumatologist or immunologist before supplementing.</li>
        <li><strong>People taking blood thinners:</strong> Melatonin may increase the anticoagulant effects of warfarin and other blood-thinning medications, raising bleeding risk.</li>
        <li><strong>People taking immunosuppressants:</strong> Because melatonin can stimulate immune function, it may counteract the effects of immunosuppressive medications used after organ transplantation or for autoimmune conditions.</li>
        <li><strong>People with seizure disorders:</strong> Some evidence suggests melatonin may affect seizure thresholds. Those with epilepsy should consult their neurologist before use.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>For all other adults, melatonin gummies are generally well-tolerated. However, we always recommend discussing any new supplement with your healthcare provider, particularly if you take prescription medications.</p>

