    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Melatonin Gummies</h2>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Is melatonin safe to take every night long-term?</summary>
        <p>Melatonin is considered safe for short-term nightly use — up to 3 months — in healthy adults. The American Academy of Sleep Medicine supports this position, and adverse events at standard doses (1-3mg) are uncommon and mild. Long-term safety data beyond 2 years is limited, which is why most clinicians recommend periodic breaks, such as 3 weeks on and 1 week off, to prevent psychological reliance and to assess whether the supplement is still necessary. Consult your healthcare provider before committing to nightly melatonin use for longer than 3 months, especially if you take blood thinners, immunosuppressants, or diabetes medications.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can you take too much melatonin?</summary>
        <p>Yes. While melatonin is not toxic in the traditional pharmacological sense, doses above 5mg produce supraphysiological blood levels — far above what your body naturally generates — and are associated with a higher incidence of side effects. These include next-day grogginess, headaches, nausea, dizziness, and vivid or disturbing dreams. Paradoxically, very high doses (10mg+) can actually disrupt sleep architecture rather than improve it, because they interfere with the natural rise and fall of melatonin that your circadian system depends on. The research from MIT is clear: <strong>0.3mg to 1mg was sufficient to produce physiological nighttime levels</strong>. More is not better with melatonin. Start with the lowest available dose and increase only if necessary.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Does melatonin cause dependency or addiction?</summary>
        <p>No. Melatonin does not cause physical dependency, chemical addiction, or pharmacological tolerance. This distinguishes it fundamentally from prescription sleep medications such as benzodiazepines (Xanax, Ativan) or Z-drugs (Ambien, Lunesta), which can create genuine chemical dependency with regular use. Your body does not stop producing melatonin because you take a supplement. However, some people develop a <strong>psychological reliance</strong> — they come to believe they cannot fall asleep without a gummy, even though their endogenous melatonin production remains intact. Cycling your usage (3 weeks on, 1 week off) and maintaining strong sleep hygiene habits help prevent this pattern.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>When is the best time to take melatonin gummies?</summary>
        <p>Take melatonin gummies <strong>30 to 60 minutes before your intended bedtime</strong>. Oral melatonin reaches peak blood concentration within approximately 30-90 minutes of ingestion, so this timing window ensures that peak levels coincide with when you want to fall asleep. Taking melatonin too early (2+ hours before bed) means levels may begin declining before you need them. Taking it immediately at bedtime means you may lie awake for 30-60 minutes waiting for the effect. Equally important is consistency — taking melatonin at the same time each night reinforces your circadian rhythm and trains your body to anticipate the sleep signal.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are melatonin gummies safe for kids?</summary>
        <p>Some melatonin gummies are specifically formulated for children ages 4 and older, but pediatric use should <strong>always</strong> be supervised by a pediatrician. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends exhausting behavioral interventions first — consistent bedtime routines, limited screen time before bed, a cool and dark room, and regular physical activity during the day. If a pediatrician approves melatonin, children should use the lowest available dose (0.5-1mg) and take it only as a short-term aid, not a nightly permanent fixture. Melatonin for children under 3 years old is not recommended without specific medical direction.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can pregnant or breastfeeding women take melatonin gummies?</summary>
        <p>Pregnant and breastfeeding women should <strong>not</strong> take melatonin supplements without explicit approval from their OB-GYN, midwife, or maternal-fetal medicine specialist. Melatonin is a hormone that crosses the placental barrier and is secreted into breast milk, exposing the developing fetus or nursing infant to exogenous hormonal influence. While preliminary research has not identified clear harm, the safety data is insufficient for a blanket recommendation. During pregnancy and lactation, non-hormonal sleep strategies — including magnesium supplementation (if approved by your provider), chamomile tea, sleep hygiene improvements, and relaxation techniques — are generally preferred.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What is the difference between natural and synthetic melatonin?</summary>
        <p>Most commercial melatonin supplements use <strong>synthetic melatonin</strong>, which is manufactured in laboratories and is chemically identical to the melatonin your pineal gland produces. A smaller number of products use <strong>plant-derived melatonin</strong> sourced from tart cherries, rice, or other botanical materials. The synthetic and plant-derived forms are structurally and functionally identical once absorbed — your body cannot distinguish between them. Historically, some melatonin was derived from animal pineal glands, but this practice has been largely discontinued due to contamination risks. The choice between synthetic and plant-derived is philosophical, not pharmacological — both deliver the same molecule to the same receptors with the same effects.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do melatonin gummies work better than pills or capsules?</summary>
        <p>The active ingredient — melatonin — works identically regardless of delivery format. Gummies may absorb marginally faster because they begin dissolving in the mouth, allowing some sublingual absorption, but the difference is typically 5-10 minutes at most. The real advantage of gummies is <strong>compliance</strong>. Research consistently shows that people are more likely to take supplements regularly when they enjoy the experience, and consistency is the single largest factor in whether melatonin produces meaningful results. A gummy you take every night at 9:30 PM will outperform a capsule that sits forgotten in your medicine cabinet.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

